‘man, male’. This is a Greek translation of an unknown Aramaic original; it was the name of the first of Christ's disciples, the patron saint of both Scotland and Russia. The Scottish surname   Anderson   is far more common than its Russian equivalent, <b>Andreev</b>. The personal name was popular throughout Europe in various vernacular forms (including Italian <i>Andrea</i>, French <i>André</i>, Spanish <i>Andrés</i>, Scottish, North German, and Scandinavian <i>Anders</i>, Dutch <i>Andries</i>, Hungarian <i>András</i>, Czech <i>Ondřej</i>, Polish <i>Andrzej</i> and <i>Jędrzej</i>, and Russian <i>Andrey</i>).","Americanized or Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Andrejaš</b>: from an old vernacular form of the personal name <i>Andraž</i> (from Latin <i>Andreas</i>), which is a variant of <i>Andrej</i>; see   Andrew  ."]}]},{"name":"Hynninen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Finnish Reino, Aarne, Jouni, Jyrki, Markku, Paavo, Pentti, Urho.  Scandinavian Arni.","Finnish (<b>Hänninen</b>): from the German personal name   Johannes   (or its pet form such as <i>Hänschen</i>) + the surname suffix <i>-nen</i>. German personal names were adopted in Finland during the Middle Ages; German influence was centered on the multi-cultural town of Viipuri in Karelia. This name is found typically in central and east-central areas of Finland."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannes","meanings":["German and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Johannes</i> (see   John  )."]}]},{"name":"Staffan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":[", German, Dutch, Polish, and South Slavic form of   Stephen  , now also quite commonly used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephan","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , preserving the vowels of the Greek name."]},{"name":"Steffen","meanings":["form of   Stefan ."]},{"name":"Stephen","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":36,"year":"1436","julianDay":2245548,"title":"The Engelbrekt Rebellion","description":"Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, a Swedish mine owner and statesman, led a rebellion against Eric of Pomerania, King of the Kalmar Union. Sweden was upset with the Danes' interference with Swedish exports and unjust collection of taxes. The Engelbrekt Rebellion led to the deposing of Eric of Pomerania and the eventual dissolution of the Kalmar Union.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Staffan Andersson Hynninen was born in 1400, in Grangärde, Dalarna, Sweden, his father, Anders Hynninen, was 21 and his mother, Ella Gertrud Johansdotter, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Ella Getrud Johansdotter. He died in 1475, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1400–1475":"1400–1475","1405–1480":"1405–1480","1437–1510":"1437–1510","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1480":"1480","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Grangärde, Dalarna, Sverige":"Grangärde, Dalarna, Rootsi","Grangärde, Dalarna, Sweden":"Grangärde, Dalarna, Rootsi","Grangärde, Ludvika, Dalarna, Sverige":"Grangärde, Ludvika, Dalarna, Rootsi"},"fi":{"1400–1475":"1400–1475","1405–1480":"1405–1480","1437–1510":"1437–1510","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1480":"1480","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Grangärde, Dalarna, Sverige":"Grangärde, Dalarna, Ruotsi","Grangärde, Dalarna, Sweden":"Grangärde, Dalarna, Ruotsi","Grangärde, Ludvika, Dalarna, Sverige":"Grangärde, Ludvika, Dalarna, Ruotsi"},"fr":{"1400–1475":"1400–1475","1405–1480